Hi @shnizzedy , Coming back to this. I added the correlation test screenshot above. I was thinking if the splitting of dimensions is better in the function itself or like you suggested .. in the node (higher) level ?
If this still works as-is, I vote we merge it and move this conversation to a new issue to further optimize. Right now its doing 1 voxel timeseries at a time inside the function and with feedback from Connor I tested running few blocks instead of a single voxel timeseries, which improves the speed a lot keeping the memory usage the same. I see benefits to do it in the node level.. especially because I was thinking only to split up if the image is too large relative to the allocated/available memory. Would there be a way, I mean would it be easy to check for this available memory and then split accordingly (chunks of appropriate sizes)? If we can determine "too large" and "appropriate sizes" based on the raw data, it should be pretty easy. If we need some preprocessing to be done before we can figure those out, it would be a lot trickier since we build the whole graph before running. It could be something like %%{ init: { (14 more lines were trimmed) where appropriate_sizes is a Function node that calculates the number or size of chunks and passes that along to the chunk-splitting node.
